<keyStep id="833504F98D3FFFB2FF5DFCD19E5B23D7" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<subSubSection id="70DB4FD78D3FFFB2FF5DFCD19E582362" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="key">
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DFCD19E582362" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DFCD19E582362" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
1. Abdomen with glabrous region limited to the medial line of ventrites 3–5 (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FE07FCFB9E222402" box="[461,516,871,892]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Prosternum divided into lateral halves for the reception of the anterior portion of the sternal keel. Dorsal surface sometimes appearing greenish. Eastern 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FF02FC4E9D682499" box="[200,334,978,999]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">United States</collectingCountry>
, eastern coast of 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FDC8FC4E9E6B2499" box="[514,589,978,999]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and extreme southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FE52FC709DFB237F" box="[408,477,1004,1025]" name="Canada" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Canada</collectingCountry>
........................... ................. 
<taxonomicName id="FFC167DF8D3FFFB2FEFBFB9A9E582362" box="[305,638,1030,1052]" class="Liliopsida" family="Restionaceae" genus="Hydrophilus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ovatus" subGenus="Dibolocelus">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FEFBFB9A9E582362" bold="true" box="[305,638,1030,1052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FEFBFB9A9D8F2362" bold="true" box="[305,425,1030,1052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Hydrophilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FE71FB9A9E0A2362" bold="true" box="[443,556,1030,1052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Dibolocelus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FD8AFB9A9E582362" bold="true" box="[576,638,1030,1052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">ovatus</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DFBB59E5B23D7" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DFBB59E5B23D7" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
1′. Abdomen with glabrous region not limited to medial line of ventrites 3–5 (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FDC5FBD89E572327" box="[527,625,1092,1114]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Figs. 4–5</figureCitation>
). Prosternum strongly emarginated posteriorly but not divided into lateral halves. Dorsal surface never appearing greenish......................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="833504F98D3FFFB2FF5DFB2A9E5B22BC" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DFB2A9E5B222E" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DFB2A9E5B222E" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
2. Specimens usually smaller (&lt;
<quantity id="FF39B1B98D3FFFB2FE2AFB2A9E0E23B5" box="[480,552,1206,1227]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" unit="mm" value="32.0">32 mm</quantity>
). Collectively, the glabrous regions of ventrites 2–5 from a distinctive “kite” shaped glabrous region (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FF05FA9A9D212265" box="[207,263,1286,1307]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Widespread from 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FE70FA9A9E262265" box="[442,512,1286,1307]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FDD7FA9A9E5C2265" box="[541,634,1286,1307]" name="Argentina" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, but not yet known from the Nearctic region ..... .............................. 
<taxonomicName id="FFC167DF8D3FFFB2FEBCFAA69E5B222E" authorityName="Brulle" authorityYear="1837" box="[374,637,1338,1360]" class="Liliopsida" family="Restionaceae" genus="Hydrophilus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ensifer">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FEBCFAA69E5B222E" bold="true" box="[374,637,1338,1360]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FEBCFAA69DCA222E" bold="true" box="[374,492,1338,1360]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Hydrophilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FE37FAA69E03222E" bold="true" box="[509,549,1338,1360]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">s. str</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FDF7FAA69E5B222E" bold="true" box="[573,637,1338,1360]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">ensifer</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DFAC29E5B22BC" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DFAC29E5B22BC" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
2′. Specimens usually larger (&gt; 
<quantity id="FF39B1B98D3FFFB2FE1AFAC29E3E220D" box="[464,536,1374,1395]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" unit="mm" value="34.0">34 mm</quantity>
). Abdominal pubescence broad, not forming a “kite” shaped glabrous region on ventrites 2–5 (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FF05FA319D0A22BC" box="[207,300,1453,1475]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Figs. 5–6</figureCitation>
)..................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DFA4C9E5821FA" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DFA4C9E5821FA" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyStep id="833504F98D3FFFB2FF5DFA4C9E5821FA" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
3. Antennal cupule with little to moderate elongation ca. 1.2–2x as long as wide. Abdominal glabrous region as in 
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FE5AF9999DEF2164" box="[400,457,1541,1562]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
. Fifth protarsomere of the male expanded (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FE6EF9BC9DF8214B" box="[420,478,1568,1589]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,238,617,636]" captionTargetBox="[173,652,194,593]" captionTargetId="figure-108@2.[172,659,183,593]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–2. Hydrophilus species, male protarsi." pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), but with a distinctly obtuse angle. Continental 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FE36F9A69E5C2131" box="[508,634,1594,1615]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">United States</collectingCountry>
, southern half of 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FEAFF9C99D8A2114" box="[357,428,1621,1642]" name="Canada" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Canada</collectingCountry>
, and northern 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FDFFF9C99E5A2114" box="[565,636,1621,1642]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Mexico</collectingCountry>
..................... 
<taxonomicName id="FFC167DF8D3FFFB2FE8EF9F29E5821FA" authorityName="Say. A" authorityYear="1823" box="[324,638,1646,1668]" class="Liliopsida" family="Restionaceae" genus="Hydrophilus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FE8EF9F29E5821FA" bold="true" box="[324,638,1646,1668]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FE8EF9F29D9D21FA" bold="true" box="[324,443,1646,1668]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Hydrophilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FE06F9F29DD321FA" bold="true" box="[460,501,1646,1668]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">s. str</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FDC4F9F29E5821FA" bold="true" box="[526,638,1646,1668]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">triangularis</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="387E1C5C8D3FFFB2FF5DF90E98B22609" blockId="1.[151,638,845,1729]" lastBlockId="1.[734,1172,194,375]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead id="8330BF698D3FFFB2FF5DF90E9E5B21BF" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">3′. Antennal cupule greatly elongated ca. three times as long as wide. Abdominal gla-</keyLead>
<subSubSection id="70DB4FD78D3FFFB2FD14FF5E98B22609" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="multiple">
brous region as in 
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FC53FF5E9FF027A9" box="[921,982,194,215]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,237,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[180,1164,810,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-126@2.[172,1193,762,1663]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 3–6. Abdominal ventrites of Hydrophilus species, showing extent of medial glabrous region. 3) H. ovatus;" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
. Fifth protarsomere in males greatly expanded (
<figureCitation id="A0FA00D98D3FFFB2FC24FF41980E278C" box="[1006,1064,221,242]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[197,238,617,636]" captionTargetBox="[173,652,194,593]" captionTargetId="figure-108@2.[172,659,183,593]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–2. Hydrophilus species, male protarsi." pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the plate exhibiting a nearly right angle. 
<collectingRegion id="FA05D2BE8D3FFFB2FBF6FF6B98B62672" box="[1084,1168,247,268]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Arizona</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="FA05D2BE8D3FFFB2FD14FE8E9F642659" box="[734,834,274,295]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="FA05D2BE8D3FFFB2FC85FE8E9FAC2659" box="[847,906,274,295]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Texas</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="FA05D2BE8D3FFFB2FC08FE8E982E2659" box="[962,1032,274,295]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Florida</collectingRegion>
in the 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FB98FE8E9F30263F" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">United States</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="40D65CCC8D3FFFB2FCE8FEB09F4C263F" box="[802,874,300,321]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, Central America, West Indies, and northern South America........................... ....................... 
<taxonomicName id="FFC167DF8D3FFFB2FCA1FEFD98B22609" authorityName="Laporte de Castelnau" authorityYear="1840" box="[875,1172,353,375]" class="Liliopsida" family="Restionaceae" genus="Hydrophilus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FCA1FEFD98B22609" bold="true" box="[875,1172,353,375]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FCA1FEFD9FC52609" bold="true" box="[875,995,353,375]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Hydrophilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FC3DFEFD98032609" bold="true" box="[1015,1061,353,375]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">s. str</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="0AB5C04E8D3FFFB2FB8AFEFD98B22609" bold="true" box="[1088,1172,353,375]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">insularis</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
